{{Infobox scientist | name = Alexander van Oudenaarden | image = VanOudenaarden2017a.jpg | caption = Alexander van Oudenaarden (2017) | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1970|03|19|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Zuidland]], [[The Netherlands]] | death_date = | death_place = | residence = [[The Netherlands]] | citizenship = [[Kingdom of The Netherlands]] | nationality = | ethnicity = | field = [[Biophysics]], [[Systems biology]], [[Synthetic biology]] | work_institution = [[Hubrecht Institute]] | alma_mater = [[Delft University of Technology]] (MSc, MSc, PhD) | doctoral_advisor = | doctoral_students = | known_for = | author_abbreviation_bot = | author_abbreviation_zoo = | prizes = | footnotes = }}
'''Alexander van Oudenaarden''' (19 March 1970) is a Dutch [[biophysicist]] and [[systems biology|systems biologist]]. He is a leading researcher in [[Stem cell|stem cell biology]], specialising in single cell techniques. In 2012 he started as director of the [[Hubrecht Institute]] and was awarded two times an ERC Advanced Grant, in 2012 and in 2017. In 2014 he became a member of the [[Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences]] ([[KNAW]]).<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.knaw.nl/nl/leden/leden/11404 |title=Alexander van Oudenaarden |language=Dutch |publisher=[[Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences]] |date= |accessdate=1 July 2015}}</ref> He was awarded the [[Spinoza Prize]] in 2017.
== Biography == Van Oudenaarden was born 19 March 1970, in [[Zuidland]], a small town in the [[Netherlands|Dutch]] province of [[South Holland]]. He studied at the [[Delft University of Technology]], where he obtained an [[Master of Science|MSc]] degree in Materials Science and Engineering (''[[cum laude]]'') and an MSc degree in Physics, both in 1993, and subsequently a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] degree in Physics (''cum laude'') in 1998 in experimental condensed matter physics, under the supervision of professor [[J.E. Mooij]]. He received the Andries Miedema Award (best doctoral research in the field of condensed matter physics in the Netherlands) for his thesis on "Quantum vortices and quantum interference effects in circuits of small tunnel junctions". In 1998, he moved to [[Stanford University]], where he was a postdoctoral researcher in the departments of Biochemistry and of Microbiology & Immunology, working on force generation of polymerising actin filaments in the [[J.A. Theriot|Theriot]] lab and a postdoctoral researcher in the department of Chemistry, working on [[Micropatterning]] of supported phospholipid bi-layers in the [[S.G. Boxer|Boxer]] lab. In 2000 he joined the department of Physics at MIT as an assistant professor, was tenured in 2004 and is now a full professor. In 2001 he received the [[National Science Foundation|NSF]] CAREER award, and was both an [[Sloan Fellowship|Alfred Sloan Research Fellow]] and the [[W. M. Keck Foundation|Keck Career Development]] Career Development Professor in Biomedical Engineering. In 2012 Alexander became the director of the Hubrecht Institute as the successor of [[Hans Clevers]]. In 2017 he received his second ''ERC Advanced Grant'', for his study titled "a single-cell genomics approach integrating gene expression, lineage, and physical interactions". He was awarded the [[Spinoza Prize]] in 2017.
He is married and has three children.
== Work == During his time at MIT his lab started with parallel lines of research in [[actin]] dynamics<ref>{{cite journal | doi= 10.1073/pnas.0837027100 | quotes= | last=Upadhyaya| first=A | first2=J. R. |last2=Chabot |first3=A. |last3=Andreeva |first4=A. |last4=Samadani |first5=A. |last5=van Oudenaarden | year=2003 | title=Probing polymerization forces by using actin-propelled lipid vesicles | journal=PNAS USA | volume=100 | issue= 8 | pages=4521–6 | pmid= 12657740 | pmc= 153588 |bibcode = 2003PNAS..100.4521U }}</ref><ref> {{cite journal | doi= 10.1016/j.cub.2003.08.051 | quotes= | last=Upadhyaya| first=A |author2=A. van Oudenaarden | year=2003 | title=Biomimetic systems for studying actin-based motility | journal=Current Biology | volume=13 | issue= 18 | pages=R734 | pmid= 13678615 }}</ref> and noise in gene networks,<ref>{{cite journal | doi= 10.1073/pnas.151588598 | quotes= | last=Thattai| first=M |author2=A. van Oudenaarden | year=2001 | title=Intrinsic noise in gene regulatory networks | journal=PNAS USA | volume=98 | issue= 15 | pages=8614–9 | pmid= 11438714 | pmc= 37484 |bibcode = 2001PNAS...98.8614T }}</ref><ref> {{cite journal | doi= 10.1038/ng869 | quotes= | last=Ozbudak| first=E. | first2=M. |last2=Thattai |first3=I. |last3=Kurtser |first4=A. D. |last4=Grossman |first5=A.|last5=van Oudenaarden | year=2002 | title=Regulation of noise in the expression of a single gene | journal=Nature Genetics | volume=31 | issue= 1 | pages=69–73 | pmid= 11967532 }}</ref><ref> {{cite journal | doi= 10.1016/S0006-3495(02)75635-X | quotes= | last=Thattai| first=M |author2=A. van Oudenaarden | year=2002 | title=Attenuation of noise in ultrasensitive signaling cascades | journal=Biophysical Journal | volume=82 | issue= 6 | pages=2943–50 | pmid= 12023217 | pmc= 1302082 |bibcode = 2002BpJ....82.2943T }}</ref> and then focused on stochasticity in gene networks<ref> {{cite journal | doi= 10.1126/science.1109090 | quotes= | last=Pedraza | first=J M |author2=A. van Oudenaarden | year=2005 | title=Noise propagation in gene networks | journal=Science | volume=307 | issue= 5717 | pages=1965–9 | pmid= 15790857 |bibcode = 2005Sci...307.1965P }}</ref><ref> {{cite journal | doi= 10.1038/ng1616 | quotes= | last=Becskei| first=A |author2=B. B. Kaufmann |author3=A. van Oudenaarden | year=2005 | title=Contributions of low molecule number and chromosomal positioning to stochastic gene expression | journal=Nature Genetics | volume=37 | issue= 9 | pages=937–44 | pmid= 16086016 }}</ref><ref> {{cite journal | doi= 10.1038/nature03524 | quotes= | last=Acar| first=M |author2=A. Becskei |author3=A. van Oudenaarden | year=2005 | title=Enhancement of cellular memory by reducing stochastic transitions | journal=Nature | volume=435 | issue= 7039 | pages=228–32 | pmid= 15889097 |bibcode = 2005Natur.435..228A }}</ref><ref> {{cite journal | doi= 10.1038/nature06395 | quotes= | last=Chabot| first=J R |author2=J. M. Pedraza |author3=P. Luitel |author4=A. van Oudenaarden | year=2007 | title=Stochastic gene expression out-of-steady-state in the cyanobacterial circadian clock | journal=Nature | volume=450 | issue= 7173 | pages=1249–52 | pmid= 18097413|bibcode = 2007Natur.450.1249C }}</ref> biological networks as control systems,<ref> {{cite journal | doi= 10.1016/j.devcel.2005.08.014 | quotes= | last=Thattai| first=M |author2=A. Becskei |author3=A. van Oudenaarden | year=2005 | title=A system of counteracting feedback loops regulates Cdc42p activity during spontaneous cell polarization | journal=Developmental Cell | volume=9 | issue= 4 | pages=565–71 | pmid= 16198298 }}</ref><ref> {{cite journal | doi= 10.1016/j.molcel.2007.05.018 | quotes= | last=Tsang| first=J |author2=J. Zhu |author3=A. van Oudenaarden | year=2007 | title=MicroRNA-mediated feedback and feedforward loops are recurrent network motifs in mammals | journal=Molecular Cell | volume=26 | issue= 5 | pages=753–67 | pmid= 17560377 | pmc= 2072999 }}</ref><ref> {{cite journal | doi= 10.1126/science.1151582 | quotes= | last=Mettetal| first=J |author2=D. Muzzey |author3=C. Gomez-Uribe |author4=A. van Oudenaarden | year=2008 | title=The frequency dependence of osmo-adaptation in Saccharomyces cerevisiae | journal=Science | volume=319 | issue= 5862 | pages=482–4 | pmid= 18218902 | pmc= 2916730 |bibcode = 2008Sci...319..482M }}</ref> and the evolution of small networks.
Today, Van Oudenaardens work at the Hubrecht Institute focuses on stochastic gene expression,<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Junker | first1 = Philipp | last2 = Alexander | title = Every cell is special: genome-wide studies add a new dimension to single-cell biology | url = | journal = Cell | volume = 157 | issue = | pages = 8–11 | doi=10.1016/j.cell.2014.02.010 | pmid=24679522}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Ji | first1 = Ni | last2 = Middelkoop | first2 = Teije | last3 = Mentink | first3 = Remco | last4 = Betist | first4 = Marco | last5 = Tonegawa | first5 = Satto | last6 = Mooijman | first6 = Dylan | last7 = Korswagen | first7 = Hendrik | last8 = Alexander | year = 2013 | title = Feedback control of gene expression variability in the Caenorhabditis elegans Wnt pathway | url = | journal = Cell | volume = 155 | issue = | pages = 869–880 | doi=10.1016/j.cell.2013.09.060 | pmid=24209624}}</ref> developing new tools for quantifying gene expression in single cells <ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Grün | first1 = Dominic | last2 = Kester | first2 = Lennart | last3 = Alexander | year = 2014 | title = Validation of noise models for single-cell transcriptomics | url = | journal = Nature Methods | volume = 11 | issue = | pages = 637–640 | doi=10.1038/nmeth.2930}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Klemm | first1 = Sandy | last2 = Semrau | first2 = Stefan | last3 = Wiebrands | first3 = Kay | last4 = Mooijman | first4 = Dylan | last5 = Faddah | first5 = Dina | last6 = Jaenisch | first6 = Rudolf | last7 = Alexander | year = 2014 | title = Transcriptional profiling of cells sorted by RNA abundance | journal = Nature Methods | volume = 11 | issue = | pages = 549–551 | doi=10.1038/nmeth.2910 | pmid=24681693 | pmc=4174458}}</ref> and MicroRNAs <ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Dong | first1 = | last2 = Kim | first2 = Dominic Grün | last3 = Alexander | year = 2013 | title = Dampening of expression oscillations by synchronous regulation of a microRNA and its target | doi = 10.1038/ng.2763 | journal = Nature Genetics | volume = 45 | issue = | pages = 1337–1344 | pmid=24036951 | pmc=3812263}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Mukherji | first1 = Shankar | last2 = Ebert | first2 = Margaret | last3 = Zheng | first3 = Grace | last4 = Tsang | first4 = John | last5 = Sharp | first5 = Phil | last6 = Alexander | year = 2011 | title = MicroRNAs can generate thresholds in target gene expression | journal = Nature Genetics | volume = 43 | issue = | pages = 854–859 | doi=10.1038/ng.905 | pmid=21857679 | pmc=3163764| url = http://dspace.mit.edu/bitstream/1721.1/74623/1/Sharp_MicroRNAs%20can.pdf }}</ref>
