{{Other ships|Christinaki (disambiguation){{!}}MV Christinaki}} {{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}} {|{{Infobox ship begin |infobox caption=}} <!-- commercial vessels --><!-- caption: yes, nodab, or <caption text> --> {{Infobox ship career |Hide header= |Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Malta|civil}} |Ship name=*{{flagicon|Ireland}} MV ''Irish Pine'' (1973-1983) *{{flagicon|Singapore}} MV ''Siganto A.S.'' (1983-1988) *{{flagicon|Singapore}} MV ''Singa Monica'' (1988-1990) *{{flagicon|Greece}} MV ''Norman Hanne'' (1990-1991) *{{flagicon|Greece}} MV ''Hanne'' (1991-1992) *{{flagicon|Malta|civil}} MV ''Christinaki'' (1992-1994) |Ship namesake= |Ship owner=Demco Maritime Ltd. |Ship operator= |Ship registry={{flagicon|Malta|civil}} [[Valletta]], Malta |Ship route= |Ship ordered= |Ship builder=Upper Clyde Shipbuilders Ltd. |Ship original cost= |Ship yard number=126 |Ship way number= |Ship laid down= |Ship launched=29 June 1972 |Ship completed=1 February 1973 |Ship christened= |Ship acquired= |Ship maiden voyage= |Ship in service=1973 |Ship out of service=3 February 1994 |Ship identification={{IMO Number|7221225}} |Ship fate=Sunk in a force 10 gale |Ship status= |Ship notes= }} {{Infobox ship characteristics |Hide header= |Header caption= |Ship class= |Ship type=[[Bulk carrier]] |Ship tonnage={{GRT|16,704}} |Ship length={{convert|174.96|m|ftin}} |Ship beam={{convert|25.6|m|ftin}} |Ship height= |Ship draught= |Ship draft= |Ship depth={{convert|9.75|m|ftin}} |Ship Armament= |Ship decks= |Ship deck clearance= |Ship ramps= |Ship ice class= |Ship sail plan= |Ship power=1 x 6cyl. 2SA Kincaid-B&W 6K74EF |Ship propulsion=Screw propeller |Ship speed=15 knots |Ship capacity= |Ship crew=27 |Ship notes= }} |}
'''MV ''Christinaki''''' was a [[Malta|Maltese]] [[bulk carrier]] which sank in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] {{convert|240|nmi|km}} south west of Ireland during a force 10 gale with a cargo of scrap metal and 27 crew while she was travelling from [[Liverpool]], [[United Kingdom]] to [[Vera Cruz (city)|Vera Cruz]].<ref name=JGM>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/survivors-sighted-as-rescuers-hunt-cargo-ship-lost-in-storm-1391867.html |title=Survivors sighted as rescuers hunt cargo ship lost in storm |publisher=independent.co.uk |date=4 February 1994 |accessdate=3 February 2016}}</ref>
== Construction == ''Christinaki'' was constructed in 1973 at the Upper Clyde Shipbuilders Ltd. shipyard in [[Govan]], [[Scotland]], [[United Kingdom]]. She was launched on 29 June 1972 and completed on 1 February 1973 for [[Irish Shipping]] and was named ''MV Irish Pine''<ref name="clydebuilt">{{cite web |title=MV Irish Pine |publisher=Clydebuilt Database |year=2014 |url=http://www.clydesite.co.uk/clydebuilt/ireland/IRISH_PINE_126.html |accessdate=2016-02-04 }}</ref> and switched owners and names several times before her demise in 1994. The ship was {{convert|174.96|m|ftin}} long, with a beam of {{convert|25.6|m|ftin}} and a depth of {{convert|9.75|m|ftin}}. The ship was assessed at {{GRT|16,704}}. She had a 1 x 6cyl. 2SA Kincaid-B&W 6K74EF engine driving a single screw propeller, the engine was rated at 11.400 b.h.p.<ref name="clydebuilt"/><ref name=JSM>{{cite web |url=http://www.parthenon.uk.com/disaster-christinaki.htm |title=Loss of the Bulk Carrier "MV Christinaki" |publisher=parthenon.uk.com |date=2009 |accessdate=3 February 2016}}</ref>
== Sinking == On 2 February 1994, ''Christinaki'' left [[Liverpool]], [[United Kingdom]] with a cargo of scrap metal bound for [[Vera Cruz (city)|Vera Cruz]].
The following day the weather worsened and the ship was soon caught in a force 10 storm {{convert|240|nmi|km}} south west of Ireland with 35 feet (10 meter) waves ramming her deck. The ship quickly took on water as the hold hatch covers failed. The crew knowing that the ship was taken in water and was in mortal danger quickly radioed a distress signal at 4 PM. The last radio contact was made at 4:30 PM, at this time the ships is believed to have sunk. Rescuers searched the following day for any survivors near the last known location of the ship but it was soon clear that the 27 Greek and Filipino crew members had perished.<ref name=ASM>{{cite web |url=http://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?58850 |title=MV Christinaki [+1994] |publisher=Wrecksite |date=1 August 2008 |accessdate=3 February 2016}}</ref>
== Wreck == The wreck's current position is unknown.
