'''Massa''' (1930 &ndash; 30 December 1984) was the oldest living [[gorilla]], reaching an age of 54 years, until his death in 1984.<ref name=Massa>{{cite web|title=All results for Massa The Gorilla |url=http://search.ancestry.com/cgi-bin/sse.dll?gsln=Massa%20the%20Gorilla&gsfn=&gl=allgs |website=http://search.ancestry.com/ |accessdate=30 December 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827191220/http://search.ancestry.com/cgi-bin/sse.dll?gsln=Massa%20the%20Gorilla&gsfn=&gl=allgs |archivedate=27 August 2016 |df= }}</ref>

Massa was born in the wild in [[Ghana]].  He was shipped to [[United States|America]] at an early age and his first owner was [[Brooklyn]] [[Eccentricity (behaviour)|eccentric]] [[Gertrude Lintz]].  In 1935, after accidentally spilling water on Massa, which startled him severely, Mrs. Lintz decided to sell him to the [[Philadelphia Zoo]].<ref>[http://articles.philly.com/2000-03-31/news/25607542_1_massa-gorillas-african-lowland A Farewell To Massa, Daily News, by Frank Dougherty, Jan. 2, 1985]</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1985/01/01/us/54-year-old-gorilla-oldest-in-captivity-dies-in-philadelphia.html, NY Times, 54-YEAR-OLD GORILLA, OLDEST IN CAPTIVITY, DIES IN PHILADELPHIA, UPI,  January 1, 1985 ]</ref>{{deadlink|date=January 2017}}

In his prime, Massa weighed 400&nbsp;lbs.

Massa lived at the zoo until his death from a [[stroke]] on 30 December 1984, following a special birthday party held by the zoo, complete with a special cake and a live [[dixieland]] band.  He was buried within the grounds of the zoo.

The film ''[[Buddy (1997 film)|Buddy]]'' was based on the life of Massa (with some elements from the life of another of Mrs. Lintz's gorillas, [[Gargantua (gorilla)|Gargantua]], who was known at the time as Buddy).

